\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 The Association Between Sleep Duration and Immune Function in Healthy Adults: A Prospective Observational Study\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Background:
\f0\b0  Sleep is a fundamental physiological process essential for immune system regulation and overall health. Both short and long sleep durations have been associated with adverse health outcomes, including increased susceptibility to infections. However, the relationship between habitual sleep duration and immune biomarkers in healthy adults remains incompletely understood.\

\f1\b Objective:
\f0\b0  To examine the association between sleep duration and immune function, assessed through inflammatory and immunological biomarkers, in a cohort of healthy adults.\

\f1\b Methods:
\f0\b0  A prospective observational study was conducted involving 180 healthy adults aged 25\'9655 years. Participants were categorized into three groups based on self-reported average sleep duration: short sleep (<6 hours), normal sleep (6\'968 hours), and long sleep (>8 hours). Immune function was assessed using serum levels of C-reactive protein (CRP), interleukin-6 (IL-6), tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-\uc0\u945 ), and natural killer (NK) cell activity. Data were analyzed using multivariate regression models adjusted for potential confounders.\

\f1\b Results:
\f0\b0  Short sleep duration was significantly associated with elevated CRP, IL-6, and TNF-\uc0\u945  levels and reduced NK cell activity compared to normal sleep duration (p < 0.01). Long sleep duration was also associated with higher inflammatory markers, though to a lesser extent. Normal sleep duration was associated with optimal immune biomarker profiles.\

\f1\b Conclusion:
\f0\b0  Both insufficient and excessive sleep durations are associated with altered immune function in healthy adults. Maintaining a regular sleep duration of 6\'968 hours may support optimal immune health and reduce low-grade systemic inflammation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
