\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Sleep plays a critical role in maintaining physiological homeostasis, cognitive performance, metabolic regulation, and immune competence. Increasing evidence suggests that sleep and immune function are closely interconnected, with bidirectional influences. Immune activation can alter sleep architecture, while sleep deprivation can impair immune responses and increase vulnerability to infectious and inflammatory diseases.\
Modern lifestyles have led to widespread sleep disturbances and reduced sleep duration, particularly among working-age adults. Epidemiological studies have linked short sleep duration to increased risk of cardiovascular disease, metabolic disorders, depression, and mortality. Conversely, long sleep duration has also been associated with adverse health outcomes, though the underlying mechanisms remain unclear.\
From an immunological perspective, sleep is thought to enhance host defense by promoting the production of cytokines and facilitating immune cell trafficking. Experimental studies have demonstrated that acute sleep deprivation can reduce natural killer (NK) cell activity and alter cytokine profiles. However, most existing research has focused on acute or experimental sleep deprivation rather than habitual sleep patterns in healthy populations.\
Understanding how regular sleep duration influences immune biomarkers in otherwise healthy individuals may provide valuable insights into disease prevention and public health strategies. This study aims to investigate the association between habitual sleep duration and immune function markers in a cohort of healthy adults.\
