\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Discussion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This study demonstrates a significant association between habitual sleep duration and immune function in healthy adults. Short sleep duration was associated with a pro-inflammatory state and impaired innate immune function, as evidenced by elevated inflammatory markers and reduced NK cell activity. These findings support the hypothesis that chronic insufficient sleep may compromise immune defense and increase susceptibility to inflammatory conditions.\
The observed association between long sleep duration and elevated inflammatory markers is consistent with previous epidemiological studies linking excessive sleep to adverse health outcomes. While the mechanisms underlying this relationship are not fully understood, long sleep duration may reflect underlying health issues, reduced physical activity, or altered circadian regulation.\
The biological mechanisms linking sleep and immune function are complex and likely involve neuroendocrine pathways, including dysregulation of cortisol and sympathetic nervous system activity. Sleep loss has been shown to increase pro-inflammatory cytokine production, which may contribute to chronic low-grade inflammation.\
Strengths of this study include the assessment of multiple immune biomarkers and adjustment for a wide range of confounding factors. Limitations include reliance on self-reported sleep duration and the observational design, which precludes causal inference. Future studies using objective sleep measurements and longitudinal designs are warranted.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Conclusion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Habitual sleep duration is significantly associated with immune function in healthy adults. Both insufficient and excessive sleep are linked to increased inflammatory markers and altered immune responses. Promoting healthy sleep duration of 6\'968 hours per night may be an important strategy for maintaining optimal immune health and preventing chronic disease.\
